data.content:
Three EF Core 10 breaking changes hit your code directly:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — now takes a regular lambda, not an expression tree

Your entire expression tree construction is no longer needed. Replace with:

```csharp
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

The `Action<...>` signature replaces `Expression<Func<...>>`, so conditional setters are just normal C# control flow now.

---

### 2. Complex type column names — two changes

**a) Same-named properties across complex types are uniquified.** Your `ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street` will get disambiguated column names (e.g., `Street1`). Pin them explicitly:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b => {
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, sa =>
        sa.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("ShippingAddress_Street"));
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, ba =>
        ba.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_Street"));
});
```

**b) Nested complex types now use the full path.** `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` was mapped to `BillingAddress_City` — it's now `Payment_BillingAddress_City`. If you need the old name:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>(b => {
    b.ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment, p =>
        p.ComplexProperty(pay => pay.BillingAddress, ba =>
            ba.Property(a => a.City).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City")));
});
```

Both changes will generate rename migrations. Use `HasColumnName()` to preserve existing column names and avoid data-disrupting migrations.

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method gained a `string logCommandText` parameter. Update your implementation:

```csharp
public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
    IRelationalConnection connection, DbCommand command,
    DbContext context, Guid commandId, Guid connectionId,
    DateTimeOffset startTime,
    string logCommandText)   // ← new: redacted SQL safe for logging
{ /* logging — use logCommandText instead of command.CommandText for logs */ }
```

`logCommandText` contains SQL with constants redacted; `command.CommandText` has the actual SQL. Apply the same fix to any other methods you implement from this interface (`CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc.).
